### AO Risk Determination Statement

After reviewing the complete authorization package, consulting the Privacy Officer and System Owner, and conducting a direct review session with the ISSO, the Authorizing Official reached the following determination:

---

**RISK DETERMINATION STATEMENT**
**System:** MyClinic OpenMRS Electronic Health Record System (MCOPENMRS-001)
**Authorizing Official:** Executive Director, MyClinic
**Date:** [authorization date]

**Risk Determination:** The residual risk of operating the MyClinic OpenMRS Electronic Health Record System is **LOW TO MODERATE** and is acceptable for authorization to operate, subject to the conditions and commitments described below.

**Basis for Determination:**

The system's core security controls — encryption of ePHI at rest and in transit, multi-factor authentication, network boundary protection, audit logging and monitoring, and incident response capability — are implemented, verified by independent assessment, and operating as intended. The independent assessment identified no High-severity findings and three Moderate findings, all of which were remediated before this authorization package was submitted.

The residual risk is concentrated in one area: clinical operational preparedness for EHR downtime events. The technical recovery capability (backup, restoration, RTO of 4 hours demonstrated) is in place. The gap is in documented and tested procedures for clinical staff to operate safely during the recovery window. This gap has patient care implications that elevate its significance beyond a standard compliance finding for a High-impact clinical system.

The ten open POA&M items are acknowledged. Nine are Low severity with appropriate compensating controls. POA&M Item 001 (clinical downtime procedures) is Moderate severity and is the primary basis for the conditions below.

**Authorization Decision:** AUTHORIZATION TO OPERATE — CONDITIONAL

**Conditions:**

*Condition 1 — Clinical Downtime Procedures (CP-2):*
The clinical downtime procedures must be completed, reviewed by clinical leadership, and tested with clinical staff within 90 days of this authorization date. Progress will be reviewed directly by the Authorizing Official at a 45-day check-in. Clinical leadership review must be scheduled within 14 days of this authorization date.

*Condition 2 — Paper Record Handling Protocol:*
The CP-2 scope must include a paper record handling protocol covering: PHI access controls during downtime, paper record storage, and post-recovery reconciliation into the EHR. This was identified by the Privacy Officer as a PHI control gap during the R-2 consultation.

*Condition 3 — POA&M Quarterly Reporting:*
The ISSO will provide a POA&M status report to the Authorizing Official quarterly, beginning [date + 90 days]. The report will document all items closed, all items with revised target dates (with rationale), and any new items added through the continuous monitoring program.

*Condition 4 — AO Notification for Material Risk Changes:*
The ISSO will notify the Authorizing Official immediately if: a security incident affects patient data, a new High-severity vulnerability is identified, or any change to the system boundary, data types, or threat environment materially alters the system's risk profile. Any of these events may trigger an interim authorization review.

**Authorization Period:** Three years from authorization date, subject to the conditions above and ongoing continuous monitoring. Annual review of the continuous monitoring program output and POA&M status will inform whether early re-authorization is warranted.

**Authorizing Official Signature:** _______________________ Date: _______

