## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The AO's question about the clinical downtime procedures and the Privacy Officer's expansion of that scope — to include paper record handling and post-recovery reconciliation — reminded me of the circumstances of the **2017 Nuance Communications ransomware attack**, which disrupted clinical documentation systems for several major health systems for weeks.

Nuance provides transcription and clinical documentation services. The NotPetya ransomware that hit Nuance in June 2017 took their systems offline for over a month. Health systems that relied on Nuance for clinical documentation found themselves needing to document encounters through alternative means — and the organizations with tested downtime documentation procedures adapted significantly faster than those without them.

But one of the less-discussed aspects of that incident was the paper-to-electronic reconciliation challenge after systems were restored. Weeks of paper-based encounter documentation needed to be entered into EHRs. The reconciliation process was labor-intensive, error-prone, and — in some cases — incomplete. Entries made during the downtime period on paper that were not fully reconciled into the EHR created gaps in the longitudinal patient record.

The Privacy Officer's addition to the CP-2 scope — specifically the post-recovery reconciliation protocol — addresses exactly this risk. It is not enough to know how to document on paper during downtime; there needs to be a structured process for getting that documentation accurately back into the system when it is restored. The Nuance incident demonstrates that for extended downtime events, the reconciliation process is where data integrity risk accumulates, not just during the downtime period itself.

